Coronavirus travel health
Check the latest information on risk from COVID-19 for Guinea on the TravelHealthPro website
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
International travel
Guinea’s land borders are closed and commercial flights are suspended until further notice. There are currently no commercial options available to leave Guinea.
Entry and borders
See Entry requirements to find out what you will need to do when you arrive in Guinea.
Travel in Guinea
The state of emergency was extended on 15 June for a period of up to 30 days. There is a curfew in Conakry, Coyah and Dubréka from 11pm to 4am. Conakry Airport is closed to commercial flights until further notice. Guinea’s borders are currently closed.
From 18 April everyone must wear a mask and those not wearing masks will be fined 30,000 GNF.
Public places and services
There is a limit of 30 people assembling for marriage, baptism and funeral services in Conakry and 100 people in the interior of the country. Most schools, mosques and bars are closed. Some schools and places of worship reopened in June in areas without recent Covid-19 infections.
Healthcare in Guinea
For contact details for English speaking doctors, visit our list of healthcare providers.
Your emotional and mental wellbeing is important. Read guidance on how to look after your mental wellbeing and mental health.
View Health for further details on healthcare in Guinea.
If you have any health concerns relating to coronavirus, call the local government helpline L’Agence Nationale de Securité Santé (ANSS) +224 629 995 656 / +224 626 069 797. Information on coronavirus is also on the government website.
Those testing positive for coronavirus must remain at the government coronavirus health centre.
Finance
For information on financial support you can access whilst abroad, visit our financial assistance guidance.
Returning to the UK
When you return, you must follow the rules for entering the UK.
Further information
L’Agence Nationale de la Sécurité Sanitaire gives Guinea’s overarching guidance. www.anss-guinee.org
